column2: A strange seed was planted on its back at birth. The plant sprouts and grows with this POK‚MON.
column3: When the bulb on its back grows large, it appears to lose the ability to stand on its hind legs.
column4: The plant blooms when it is absorbing solar energy. It stays on the move to seek sunlight.
column6: Obviously prefers hot places. When it rains, steam is said to spout from the tip of its tail.
column7: When it swings its burning tail, it elevates the temperature to unbearably high levels.
column8: Spits fire that is hot enough to melt boulders. Known to cause forest fires unintentionally.
column11: After birth, its back swells and hardens into a shell. Powerfully sprays foam from its mouth.
column12: Often hides in water to stalk unwary prey. For swimming fast, it moves its ears to maintain balance.
column13: A brutal POK‚MON with pressurized water jets on its shell. They are used for high speed tackles.
column15: Its short feet are tipped with suction pads that enable it to tirelessly climb slopes and walls.
column16: This POK‚MON is vulnerable to attack while its shell is soft, exposing its weak and tender body.
column17: In battle, it flaps its wings at high speed to release highly toxic dust into the air.
column18: Often found in forests, eating leaves. It has a sharp venomous stinger on its head.
column19: Almost incapable of moving, this POK‚MON can only harden its shell to protect itself from predators.
column20: Flies at high speed and attacks using its large venomous stingers on its forelegs and tail.

column2: It can go for days without eating a single morsel. In the bulb on its back, it stores energy.
column3: The bulb on its back grows by drawing energy. It gives off an aroma when it is ready to bloom.
column4: The flower on its back catches the sun?s rays. The sunlight is then absorbed and used for energy.
column6: The flame at the tip of its tail makes a sound as it burns. You can only hear it in quiet places.
column7: Tough fights could excite this POK‚MON. When excited, it may blow out bluish-white flames.
column8: When expelling a blast of super hot fire, the red flame at the tip of its tail burns more intensely.
column11: Shoots water at prey while in the water. Withdraws into its shell when in danger.
column12: When tapped, this POK‚MON will pull in its head, but its tail will still stick out a little bit.
column13: Once it takes aim at its enemy, it blasts out water with even more force than a fire hose.
column15: If you touch the feeler on top of its head, it will release a horrible stink to protect itself.
column16: Hardens its shell to protect itself. However, a large impact may cause it to pop out of its shell.
column17: Its wings, covered with poisonous powders, repel water. This allows it to fly in the rain.
column18: Beware of the sharp stinger on its head. It hides in grass and bushes where it eats leaves.
column19: Able to move only slightly. When endangered, it may stick out its stinger and poison its enemy.
column20: It has 3 poisonous stingers on its forelegs and its tail. They are used to jab its enemy repeatedly.

column2: The seed on its back is filled with nutrients. The seed grows steadily larger as its body grows.
column3: Exposure to sunlight adds to its strength. Sunlight also makes the bud on its back grow larger.
column4: By spreading the broad petals of its flower and catching the sun?s rays, it fills its body with power.
column6: The flame on its tail shows the strength of its life force. If it is weak, the flame also burns weakly.
column7: It is very hotheaded by nature, so it constantly seeks opponents. It calms down only when it wins.
column8: If CHARIZARD becomes furious, the flame at the tip of its tail flares up in a whitish-blue color.
column11: The shell is soft when it is born. It soon becomes so resilient, prodding fingers will bounce off it.
column12: It is recognized as a symbol of longevity. If its shell has algae on it, that WARTORTLE is very old.
column13: It deliberately makes itself heavy so it can withstand the recoil of the water jets it fires.
column15: For protection, it releases a horrible stench from the antenna on its head to drive away enemies.
column16: Inside the shell, it is soft and weak as it prepares to evolve. It stays motionless in the shell.
column17: It collects honey every day. It rubs honey onto the hairs on its legs to carry it back to its nest.
column18: Its poison stinger is very powerful. Its bright-colored body is intended to warn off its enemies.
column19: Although it is a cocoon, it can move a little. It can extend its poison barb if it is attacked.
column20: It can take down any opponent with its powerful poison stingers. It sometimes attacks in swarms.

column2: It carries a seed on its back right from birth. As it grows older, the seed also grows larger.
column3: If the bud on its back starts to smell sweet, it is evidence that the large flower will soon bloom.
column4: It is able to convert sunlight into energy. As a result, it is more powerful in the summertime.
column6: The flame on its tail indicates CHARMANDER?s life force. If it is healthy, the flame burns brightly.
column7: It has a barbaric nature. In battle, it whips its fiery tail around and slashes away with sharp claws.
column8: Breathing intense, hot flames, it can melt almost anything. Its breath inflicts terrible pain on enemies.
column11: The shell, which hardens soon after it is born, is resilient. If you poke it, it will bounce back out.
column12: It cleverly controls its furry ears and tail to maintain its balance while swimming.
column13: The rocket cannons on its shell fire jets of water capable of punching holes through thick steel.
column15: Its feet have suction cups designed to stick to any surface. It tenaciously climbs trees to forage.
column16: It prepares for evolution by hardening its shell as much as possible to protect its soft body.
column17: Water-repellent powder on its wings enables it to collect honey, even in the heaviest of rains.
column18: It attacks using a two-inch poison barb on its head. It can usually be found under the leaves it eats.
column19: From this form, it will grow into an adult. As its body becomes softer, the external shell hardens.
column20: It has three poison barbs. The barb on its tail secretes the most powerful poison.

column2: While it is young, it uses the nutrients that are stored in the seeds on its back in order to grow.
column3: The bulb on its back grows as it absorbs nutrients. The bulb gives off a pleasant aroma when it blooms.
column4: As it warms itself and absorbs the sunlight, its flower petals release a pleasant fragrance.
column6: If it?s healthy, the flame on the tip of its tail will burn vigorously, even if it gets a bit wet.
column7: If it becomes agitated during battle, it spouts intense flames, incinerating its surroundings.
column8: It uses its wings to fly high. The temperature of its fire increases as it gains experience in battle.
column11: When it feels threatened, it draws its legs inside its shell and sprays water from its mouth.
column12: Its long, furry tail is a symbol of longevity, making it quite popular among older people.
column13: It firmly plants its feet on the ground before shooting water from the jets on its back.
column15: It crawls into foliage where it camouflages itself among leaves that are the same color as its body.
column16: This is its pre-evolved form. At this stage, it can only harden, so it remains motionless to avoid attack.
column17: It flits from flower to flower, collecting honey. It can even identify distant flowers in bloom.
column18: The barb on top of its head secretes a strong poison. It uses this toxic barb to protect itself.
column19: Nearly incapable of movement, it leans against stout trees while waiting for its evolution.
column20: It uses sharp, poisonous stings to defeat prey, then takes the victim back to its nest for food.

column2: BULBASAUR can be seen napping in bright sunlight. There is a seed on its back. By soaking up the sun?s rays, the seed grows progressively larger.
column3: There is a bud on this POK‚MON?s back. To support its weight, IVYSAUR?s legs and trunk grow thick and strong. If it starts spending more time lying in the sunlight, it?s a sign that the bud will bloom into a large flower soon.
column4: There is a large flower on VENUSAUR?s back. The flower is said to take on vivid colors if it gets plenty of nutrition and sunlight. The flower?s aroma soothes the emotions of people.
column6: The flame that burns at the tip of its tail is an indication of its emotions. The flame wavers when Charmander is enjoying itself. If the Pok‚mon becomes enraged, the flame burns fiercely.
column7: Charmeleon mercilessly destroys its foes using its sharp claws. If it encounters a strong foe, it turns aggressive. In this excited state, the flame at the tip of its tail flares with a bluish white color.
column8: CHARIZARD flies around the sky in search of powerful opponents. It breathes fire of such great heat that it melts anything. However, it never turns its fiery breath on any opponent weaker than itself.
column11: SQUIRTLE?s shell is not merely used for protection. The shell?s rounded shape and the grooves on its surface help minimize resistance in water, enabling this POK‚MON to swim at high speeds.
column12: Its tail is large and covered with a rich, thick fur. The tail becomes increasingly deeper in color as WARTORTLE ages. The scratches on its shell are evidence of this POK‚MON?s toughness as a battler.
column13: BLASTOISE has water spouts that protrude from its shell. The water spouts are very accurate. They can shoot bullets of water with enough accuracy to strike empty cans from a distance of over 160 feet.
column15: CATERPIE has a voracious appetite. It can devour leaves bigger than its body right before your eyes. From its antenna, this POK‚MON releases a terrifically strong odor.
column16: The shell covering this POK‚MON?s body is as hard as an iron slab. METAPOD does not move very much. It stays still because it is preparing its soft innards for evolution inside the hard shell.
column17: BUTTERFREE has a superior ability to search for delicious honey from flowers. It can even search out, extract, and carry honey from flowers that are blooming over six miles from its nest.
column18: WEEDLE has an extremely acute sense of smell. It is capable of distinguishing its favorite kinds of leaves from those it dislikes just by sniffing with its big red proboscis (nose).
column19: KAKUNA remains virtually immobile as it clings to a tree. However, on the inside, it is extremely busy as it prepares for its coming evolution. This is evident from how hot the shell becomes to the touch.
column20: BEEDRILL is extremely territorial. No one should ever approach its nest - this is for their own safety. If angered, they will attack in a furious swarm.

column4: It is able to convert sunlight into energy. As a result, it is more powerful in the summertime.
column6: The flame on its tail indicates CHARMANDER?s life force. If it is healthy, the flame burns brightly.
column7: It has a barbaric nature. In battle, it whips its fiery tail around and slashes away with sharp claws.
column8: Breathing intense, hot flames, it can melt almost anything. Its breath inflicts terrible pain on enemies.
column11: The shell, which hardens soon after it is born, is resilient. If you poke it, it will bounce back out.
column12: It cleverly controls its furry ears and tail to maintain its balance while swimming.
column13: The rocket cannons on its shell fire jets of water capable of punching holes through thick steel.
column15: Its feet have suction cups designed to stick to any surface. It tenaciously climbs trees to forage.
column16: It prepares for evolution by hardening its shell as much as possible to protect its soft body.
column17: Water-repellent powder on its wings enables it to collect honey, even in the heaviest of rains.
column18: It attacks using a two-inch poison barb on its head. It can usually be found under the leaves it eats.
column19: From this form, it will grow into an adult. As its body becomes softer, the external shell hardens.
column20: It has three poison barbs. The barb on its tail secretes the most powerful poison.

column2: For some time after its birth, it grows by gaining nourishment from the seed on its back.
column3: When the bud on its back starts swelling, a sweet aroma wafts to indicate the flower?s coming bloom.
column4: After a rainy day, the flower on its back smells stronger. The scent attracts other Pok‚mon.
column6: The fire on the tip of its tail is a measure of its life. If healthy, its tail burns intensely.
column7: In the rocky mountains where Charmeleon live, their fiery tails shine at night like stars.
column8: It is said that Charizard?s fire burns hotter if it has experienced harsh battles.
column11: It shelters itself in its shell, then strikes back with spouts of water at every opportunity.
column12: It is said to live 10,000 years. Its furry tail is popular as a symbol of longevity.
column13: The jets of water it spouts from the rocket cannons on its shell can punch through thick steel.
column15: It releases a stench from its red antenna to repel enemies. It grows by molting repeatedly.
column16: A steel-hard shell protects its tender body. It quietly endures hardships while awaiting evolution.
column17: It loves the honey of flowers and can locate flower patches that have even tiny amounts of pollen.
column18: It eats its weight in leaves every day. It fends off attackers with the needle on its head.
column19: While awaiting evolution, it hides from predators under leaves and in nooks of branches.
column20: Its best attack involves flying around at high speed, striking with poison needles, then flying off.

column8: When expelling a blast of superhot fire, the red flame at the tip of its tail burns more intensely.
column11: It shelters itself in its shell, then strikes back with spouts of water at every opportunity.

column13: It crushes its foe under its heavy body to cause fainting. In a pinch, it will withdraw inside its shell.

column11: Shoots water at prey while in the water. Withdraws into its shell when in danger.
column12: It is said to live 10,000 years. Its furry tail is popular as a symbol of longevity.
column13: The pressurized water jets on this brutal Pok‚mon?s shell are used for high-speed tackles.
column15: Its feet have suction cups designed to stick to any surface. It tenaciously climbs trees to forage.
column16: This Pok‚mon is vulnerable to attack while its shell is soft, exposing its weak and tender body.
column17: The wings are protected by rain-repellent dust. As a result, this Pok‚mon can fly about even in rain.
column18: Its poison stinger is very powerful. Its bright-colored body is intended to warn off its enemies.
column19: While awaiting evolution, it hides from predators under leaves and in nooks of branches.
column20: May appear in a swarm. Flies at violent speeds, all the while stabbing with the toxic stinger on its rear.

column2: Bulbasaur can be seen napping in bright sunlight. There is a seed on its back. By soaking up the sun?s rays, the seed grows progressively larger.
column3: There is a bud on this Pok‚mon?s back. To support its weight, Ivysaur?s legs and trunk grow thick and strong. If it starts spending more time lying in the sunlight, it?s a sign that the bud will bloom into a large flower soon.
column4: There is a large flower on Venusaur?s back. The flower is said to take on vivid colors if it gets plenty of nutrition and sunlight. The flower?s aroma soothes the emotions of people.
column6: The flame that burns at the tip of its tail is an indication of its emotions. The flame wavers when Charmander is enjoying itself. If the Pok‚mon becomes enraged, the flame burns fiercely.
column7: Charmeleon mercilessly destroys its foes using its sharp claws. If it encounters a strong foe, it turns aggressive. In this excited state, the flame at the tip of its tail flares with a bluish white color.
column8: Charizard flies around the sky in search of powerful opponents. It breathes fire of such great heat that it melts anything. However, it never turns its fiery breath on any opponent weaker than itself.
column11: Squirtle?s shell is not merely used for protection. The shell?s rounded shape and the grooves on its surface help minimize resistance in water, enabling this Pok‚mon to swim at high speeds.
column12: Its tail is large and covered with a rich, thick fur. The tail becomes increasingly deeper in color as Wartortle ages. The scratches on its shell are evidence of this Pok‚mon?s toughness as a battler.
column13: Blastoise has water spouts that protrude from its shell. The water spouts are very accurate. They can shoot bullets of water with enough accuracy to strike empty cans from a distance of over 160 feet.
column15: Caterpie has a voracious appetite. It can devour leaves bigger than its body right before your eyes. From its antenna, this Pok‚mon releases a terrifically strong odor.
column16: The shell covering this Pok‚mon?s body is as hard as an iron slab. Metapod does not move very much. It stays still because it is preparing its soft innards for evolution inside the hard shell.
column17: Butterfree has a superior ability to search for delicious honey from flowers. It can even search out, extract, and carry honey from flowers that are blooming over six miles from its nest.
column18: Weedle has an extremely acute sense of smell. It is capable of distinguishing its favorite kinds of leaves from those it dislikes just by sniffing with its big red proboscis (nose).
column19: Kakuna remains virtually immobile as it clings to a tree. However, on the inside, it is extremely busy as it prepares for its coming evolution. This is evident from how hot the shell becomes to the touch.
column20: Beedrill is extremely territorial. No one should ever approach its nest?this is for their own safety. If angered, they will attack in a furious swarm.

column15: When attacked by bird Pok‚mon, it resists by releasing a terrifically strong odor from its antennae, but it often becomes their prey.
column16: Its shell is filled with its soft innards. It doesn?t move much because of the risk it might carelessly spill its innards out.
column17: Close examination of its large eyes reveals that each eye is composed of a myriad of tiny eyes.

column15: It?s easy to catch, and it grows quickly, making it one of the top recommendations for novice Pok‚mon Trainers.
column16: Its shell is hard, but it?s still just a bug shell. It?s been known to break, so intense battles with it should be avoided.
column17: When attacked by other Pok‚mon, it defends itself by scattering its poisonous scales and fluttering its wings.

column15: Perhaps because it would like to grow up quickly, it has a voracious appetite, eating a hundred leaves a day.
column16: Its shell is filled with a thick liquid. All of the cells throughout its body are being rebuilt in preparation for evolution.
column17: Its wings are covered in toxic scales. If it finds bird Pok‚mon going after Caterpie, Butterfree sprinkles its scales on them to drive them off.

column15: Its body is soft and weak. In nature, its perpetual fate is to be seen by others as food.
column16: Its hard shell doesn?t crack a bit even if Pikipek pecks at it, but it will tip over, spilling out its insides.
column17: Nectar from pretty flowers is its favorite food. In fields of flowers, it has heated battles with Cutiefly for territory.
